    <section id="id1172268632616">
      <title>Carbon suboxide</title>
      <para id="id8663127">Carbon suboxide is the third oxide of carbon, C<sub>3</sub>O<sub>2</sub>. It is made from the dehydration of malonic acid, <link target-id="eip-154"/>, with P<sub>4</sub>O<sub>10</sub> above 140 °C Like carbon dioxide, the C<sub>3</sub>O<sub>2</sub> molecule is linear, with pπ-pπ bonding. </para>
      
      <equation id="eip-154"><media id="id1172264860666_media" alt="">
          <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/graphics1-3254.jpg" id="id1172264860666__onlineimage" width="500" print-width="4.5in"/>
        </media>
      </equation>


<para id="id1172266964647">Gaseous carbon suboxide has an evil smell and while stable at –78 °C it polymerizes at 25 °C. Photolysis of C<sub>3</sub>O<sub>2</sub> yields the unstable C<sub>2</sub>O. As expected from its synthesis, carbon suboxide reacts slowly with water to form malonic acid, i.e., the reverse of <link target-id="eip-154"/>; however, the reaction with stronger nuceophiles such as amines is rapid, <link target-id="eip-317"/>. </para>


